The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Top-level reshuffle at Bharti
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       Top-level reshuffle at Bharti
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                                            
	New Delhi, Aug. 5: Bharti Enterprises has announced a top-level corporate restructuring to strengthen its emerging businesses.        
	As part of the reshuffle, Rakesh Bharti Mittal and Rajan Bharti Mittal will become vice-chairmen and managing directors of Bharti Enterprises. Rakesh Mittal will also become the co-chairman of Bharti Foundation to enhance focus on social projects.         
	Rajan Mittal will look after retail, cash amp; carry and real estate. Bharti has lined up ambitious plans for retail and has tied up with global leader Wal-Mart for back-end operations.        
	With the new structure, we will be engaged with our emerging businesses at a deeper level, empower the developed businesses, strengthen the interface mechanisms of Bharti with the businesses and leverage the group functions effectively, said Sunil Bharti Mittal, chairman and group CEO of Bharti Enterprises.         
	Akhil Gupta, previously joint managing director of Bharti Airtel, will become the deputy group CEO and managing director of Bharti Enterprises.         
	He will also look after the tower infrastructure business as the vice-chairman and managing director of Bharti Infratel as well as lead the groups financial services and software business. He will continue to be on the Bharti Airtel board.         
	Manoj Kohli will become CEO and joint managing director of Bharti Airtel and will also be on the companys board.        
	As a board member, my focus will be to pursue growth strategies to achieve a superior market position, while building a strong leadership, enhancing the performance culture and retaining the agility of a small company, said Kohli.        
	Group functional directors have also been given more powers to enable them to strengthen Bhartis businesses.                                                                                                                                     
